e square root of the step number, optimizing for stability and convergence efficiency of the model training process (p. 7). Training data batching in Transformer involves handling sentences encoded via byte-pair encoding to produce manageable vocabularies—37000 tokens for English-German and 32000 for English-French. Sentence pairs are batched by approximate sequence length to ensure efficient GPU utilization, with batches containing around 25000 source and target tokens each (p. 7). Regularization techniques include dropout applied to sub-layer outputs before normalization and to embedding sums and positional encodings, with a common dropout rate of Pdrop= 0.1, providing model stability and enhancing generalization by mitigating overfitting (p. 8). The training infrastructure for the Transformer models involved using NVIDIA P100 GPUs, where the base model required about 12 hours or 100,000 training steps and the larger models extended up to 3.5 days with 300,000 training steps, illustrating how computational resources are critical for large-scale model training (p. 7). The Transformer model uses a sinusoidal positional encoding scheme intended to help with the learning of relative positions in data sequences, which may also allow the model to generalize sequence processing for lengths beyond what was seen during training, a key advantage in sequence learning tasks (p. 6)."}], 'model': 'gpt-4o', 'response_format': {'type': 'json_schema', 'json_schema': {'schema': {'$defs': {'PDFQuery': {'properties': {'query': {'title': 'Query', 'type': 'string'}, 'research_goal': {'title': 'Research Goal', 'type': 'string'}}, 'required': ['query', 'research_goal'], 'title': 'PDFQuery', 'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False}}, 'properties': {'queries': {'items': {'$ref': '#/$defs/PDFQuery'}, 'title': 'Queries', 'type': 'array'}}, 'required': ['queries'], 'title': 'PDFQueryResponse', 'type': 'object', 'additionalProperties': False}, 'name': 'PDFQueryResponse', 'strict': True