2026-04-19 18:26:09 | DEBUG    | utils | JSON_llm raw response BEFORE parsing: {"learnings":["The Transformer model employs multi-head attention, which enhances its ability to focus on different subspaces of representation simultaneously. By distributing the attention across multiple heads, the model captures various dependencies, leading to improved performance over single-head models (p. 4).","Self-attention layers in Transformer models enable each position in the sequence to attend to every other position. This characteristic often results in fewer sequential operations, outperforming recurrent layers, especially when the sequence length is smaller than the representation dimensionality (p. 6).","Dot-product attention is favored for its computational efficiency over additive attention, particularly for large dimensions. This is due to its reliance on matrix multiplication, which benefits from optimized algorithms despite potential inefficiencies with large dot products that are mitigated through scaling (p. 4).","Positional encodings are incorporated into Transformer models to provide information about the order of tokens. These encodings are critical as the model lacks recurrence and convolutions, which traditionally capture sequence order information (p. 5).","The attention mechanism allows for learning long-range dependencies by ensuring shorter path lengths than other layer types, such as recurrent layers, thus facilitating faster and more accurate learning of dependencies, especially in machine translation tasks (p. 6)."],"followUpQuestions":["How do specific dropout mechanisms function within Transformer models to reduce overfitting?"]}
